(Milne, Abelian varieties, Section 3)

On suppose les variétés irréductibles ici.

The following examples illustrate the major reasons why a rational map V
--> W may fail to extend to a regular map on the whole of V .
(a) Let W be a proper open subset of V ; then the inclusion W->V will not
extend to V . To obviate this problem, we should take W to be complete.
(b) Let C be the cuspidal plane cubic curve Y^2=X^3 . The regular map A^1 -> C,
t -> (t^2,t^3) defines an iso A^1\{0} -> C \{0}
The inverse of this isomorphism does not extend to a regular map on C,
map on C because the map on function fields doesn’t send the local ring at
0 \in A into the local ring at 0 \in C. Roughly speaking, a regular map can
only map a singularity to a worse singularity. To obviate this problem, we
should take V to be nonsingular (in fact, nonsingular is no more helpful
than normal).
(c) Let P be a point on a nonsingular surface V . It is possible to
“blow-up” P and obtain a surface W and a morphism f:W -> V which restricts
to an isomorphism W\f^{-1}(P) -> V\{P}. f^{-1}P is the projective line of
“directions” through P. The inverse of this map does not extend to all V ,
even when V and W are complete — roughly speaking, there is no preferred
direction through P , and hence no obvious choice for the image of P .

In view of these examples, the next theorem is best possible.

Th 3.1: f: V --> W application rationelle, avec V normale et W complete.
Alors f est définie sur un ouvert U, dont le complément est de codim >=2

Lemme 3.3: si f: V --> G, V non singulière et G groupe alg, alors soit f est
définie partout, soit les points où elle est non définie forme un fermé de
pure codimension 1 (ie une union fini de diviseurs premiers)

Th 3.2: si f: V --> A, V non singulière, A variété abélienne, alors f est
définie partout

Lemme 3.5.
(a) Every nonsingular curve V can be realized as an open subset of a
complete nonsingular curve C.
(b) Let C be a curve; then there is a nonsingular curve C' and a regular map
C' -> C that is an isomorphism over the set of nonsingular points of C .

Lemme 3.6.
Let V be an irreducible variety over an algebraically closed field, and let
P be a nonsingular point on V. Then the union of the irreducible curves
passing through P and nonsingular at P is dense in V.

Th 3.4: Si f: VxW->A, V, W non singulières, A variété abélienne, et VxW
géom irréductible. Alors si f(Vxw)={a}=f(vxW) (a \in A(k), v \in V(k), w
\in W(k)), alors f(VxW)={a}.

Pr: vient du théorème de rigidité
(même énoncé que le Th 3.4 où on demande juste que VxW soit géom
irréductible et V complète, A étant une variété quelconque);
que l'on applique via les deux lemmes.
